Question: I want to engage in unpaid volunteering work at a charity unrelated to
  the ECB. Do I need authorisation?
Example answer: No authorisation is required for external activities that are
  unremunerated, in the domain of culture, science, education, sport,
  charity, religion, social or other benevolent work, and not related
  to the ECB or the member of staff’s professional duties at the ECB.
  (ECB Staff Rules, pages 7–8)
Predicted answer: No — pure unpaid volunteering at a charity (i.e., an unremunerated
  activity in the domain of charity/social/benign work) does not
  require prior written authorisation. This is an explicit exception
  to the normal authorisation rule (ECB Staff Rules, §0.2.6.2, p.7).
  However, you must still: - Avoid conflicts of interest and inform
  your line manager immediately if a conflict arises from the
  volunteer activity (ECB Staff Rules, §0.2.1.1–0.2.1.3, p.5).   -
  Ensure the activity remains unremunerated and does not involve
  payments related to your ECB professional duties (ECB Staff Rules,
  §0.2.5, p.7).   - If the activity becomes remunerated or otherwise
  takes on an occupational character (or raises potential conflicts),
  obtain prior written authorisation from the Director General Human
  Resources (or Deputy) after the required consultations (ECB Staff
  Rules, §0.2.6.1, p.7).  Sources: ECB Staff Rules, §0.2.6.1–0.2.6.2
