  bonds of EUR 15,000 in a single calendar month requires prior
  authorisation. - Who: the Compliance and Governance Office (it
  receives and decides the authorisation request). - When to submit:
  at least five working days before the envisaged order date. The
  Office will decide within five working days; if it does not respond
  within five working days the transaction is deemed authorised.  Key
  details and caveats - Threshold: authorisation is required for
  transactions exceeding EUR 10,000 within any given calendar month
  (ECB Staff Rules, Art. 0.4.2.3). - Procedure and assessment: the
  Compliance and Governance Office may attach conditions and will
  assess factors such as your professional duties, whether the
  transaction is speculative, amounts, reputational risks and timing.
  Submit the request in the format specified by that Office (Art.
  0.4.2.6). - Anti‑circumvention: do not split transactions to stay
  below the EUR 10,000 threshold (prohibited). - Exceptions/special
  cases:   - Collective investment schemes: units are generally exempt
  only where you have no influence on investment policy. Schemes whose
  main purpose is to invest in assets covered by the restricted
  categories (including government securities) are not exempt and
  remain subject to authorisation (Art. 0.4.2.1).   - Discretionary
  asset management: transactions executed by a third party under a
  written asset management agreement can be exempt, but that exemption
  itself must be authorised by the Compliance and Governance Office
  and you must demonstrate you cannot influence management decisions
  (Art. 0.4.2.7).  Relevant rules cited - ECB Staff Rules, Arts.
  0.4.2.1–0.4.2.3 and Arts. 0.4.2.6–0.4.2.7 (pp.14–17).  If you want,
