  Conditions of Employment, pp.17–18.)  Details and what to do now 1.
  How pregnancy affects the unemployment allowance - Extension: The
  unemployment-allowance period is extended by 20 weeks (plus 4 weeks
  for multiple births) where birth occurs during the unemployment
  period or is expected within six weeks of its end. (ECB Conditions
  of Employment, pp.17–18.) - No automatic switch to ECB maternity
  pay: The material does not provide for an automatic transfer from
  unemployment allowance to ordinary ECB maternity pay for a former
  staff member whose contract ended before maternity leave began; the
  relevant entitlement for former staff is the 20-week extension. If
  maternity leave had already started before the contract ended,
  different rules apply (ECB pays an equivalent amount). (ECB Staff
  Rules, p.95.)  2. Documents / notifications / deadlines - Notify
  Directorate General Human Resources (DG HR) promptly that you are
  pregnant and receiving unemployment allowance, and that you have an
  expected date of confinement. - Provide a medical certificate with
  the expected date of confinement. The Staff Rules require such a
  certificate to be sent to DG HR at least three months before the
  expected date of confinement to confirm maternity-leave entitlement;
  for former staff the Conditions’ extension is implemented via DG HR
  so submit the certificate as soon as possible if you cannot meet the
  three-month timing. (ECB Staff Rules, p.95; ECB Conditions of
  Employment, pp.17–18.) - Ask DG HR for written confirmation that the
  20‑week (±4) extension will apply and for details on any
  administrative steps/forms.  3. Interaction with national benefits
  and other cover - If you claim national maternity benefits, declare
  them to DG HR as required — ECB benefits are coordinated with other
